<p>Letâ€™s say you have a solar eclipse picture on your computer, it will show up as:</p>

<p><img src="/images/solar-eclipse.jpg" alt="Solar Eclipse" /></p>

<ul>
  <li>the <strong>name</strong> of the file is <code class="highlighter-rouge">solar-eclipse</code></li>
  <li>the <strong>extension</strong> of the file is <code class="highlighter-rouge">.jpg</code></li>
</ul>

<p>A fileâ€™s extension defines the <em>type</em> of file it is (in this case, an image). For HTML files, the extension is <code class="highlighter-rouge">.html</code>.</p>

<p>By default, <strong>file extensions</strong> are hidden. In this tutorial, weâ€™ll need to be able to edit these extensions. So follow these instructions to display file extensions:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Windows</strong>: <a href="http://windows.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/show-hide-file-name-extensions">Show or hide file name extensions</a></li>
  <li><strong>Mac</strong>: <a href="https://support.apple.com/kb/PH10845?locale=en_US">Show and hide filename extensions</a></li>
</ul>

